In article <mpjCvu0Dx.LJK@netcom.com> mpj@netcom.com (Michael Paul Johnson) writes:
>
>I think the CD-ROM is really the weak link, here, unless you or your 
>customers destroy them properly.  Smashing one with a hammer and throwing 
>it in the trash leaves you open to a master puzzle maker attack.  The 
>reconstruction, would, no doubt, result in errors along the cracks, but 
>that leaves lots of plain text exposed, still.  Burning or grinding might 
>work.  This sounds messy compared to degaussing a magnetic tape and 
>possibly reusing it. ....

Someone else mentioned "microwaving" a CDROM.
Try cooking an ordinary CDROM in an ordinary microwave oven.  It may
not be as good as grinding it up, but the sparks and burning are a lot
more entertaining.


